WEBVTT

00:06.434 --> 00:13.142
The scripture reading today is from the book of Genesis, chapter 37, verses 17b to 28.

00:13.383 --> 00:16.186
They have moved on from here.

00:16.306 --> 00:19.710
The man answered, I heard them say, let's go to Dothan.

00:20.812 --> 00:24.596
So Joseph went after his brothers and found them near Dothan.

00:25.618 --> 00:27.160
But they saw him in the distance.

00:27.580 --> 00:30.484
And before he reached them, they plotted to kill him.

00:31.465 --> 00:32.807
Here comes that dreamer.

00:33.027 --> 00:35.570
They said to each other, come now.

00:35.906 --> 00:42.135
Let's kill him and throw him into one of these cisterns and say that a ferocious animal devoured him.

00:42.716 --> 00:44.758
Then we'll see what comes of his dreams.

00:46.020 --> 00:49.826
When Ruben heard this, he tried to rescue him from their hands.

00:50.727 --> 00:52.669
Let's not take his life, he said.

00:53.130 --> 00:54.412
Don't shed any blood.

00:55.233 --> 00:59.519
Throw him into this cistern here in the wilderness, but don't lay a hand on him.

01:00.400 --> 01:04.466
Ruben said this to rescue him from them and take him back to his father.

01:05.250 --> 01:14.099
So when Joseph came to his brothers, they stripped him of his robe, the ornate robe that he was wearing, and they took him and threw him in the cistern.

01:14.880 --> 01:16.061
The cistern was empty.

01:16.381 --> 01:17.703
There was no water in it.

01:18.804 --> 01:25.390
As they sat down to eat their meal, they looked up and saw a caravan of Ishmaelites coming from Gilead.

01:26.291 --> 01:33.138
Their camels were loaded with spices, balm, and myrrh, and they were on their way to take them down to Egypt.

01:33.698 --> 01:38.983
Judah said to his brothers, what will we gain if we kill our brother and cover up his blood?

01:39.724 --> 01:44.128
Come, let's sell him to the Ishmaelites and not lay our hands on him at all.

01:45.129 --> 01:48.412
After all, he is our brother, our own flesh and blood.

01:48.432 --> 01:50.514
His brothers agreed.

01:51.415 --> 02:02.546
So when the Midianites' merchants came by, his brothers pulled Joseph out of the cistern and sold him for 20 shekels of silver to the Ishmaelites who took him to Egypt.

02:03.330 --> 02:04.692
This is the word of the Lord.

02:04.752 --> 02:06.715
Thanks be to God.

02:13.867 --> 02:14.608
Thank you, Marcia.

02:14.648 --> 02:15.910
Good morning.

02:17.292 --> 02:20.517
Well, my name is Sean, one of the pastors on our team here.

02:20.537 --> 02:22.220
I'm glad to be together this morning.

02:22.260 --> 02:24.403
We were on vacation for a couple of weeks.

02:24.463 --> 02:28.330
And we all do a weird thing when one of our coworkers comes back from vacation.

02:28.430 --> 02:29.031
You know what you say?

02:29.051 --> 02:31.154
Say, aren't you glad to be back?

02:32.066 --> 02:32.366
No.

02:32.386 --> 02:39.856
I mean, I love it here, but I prefer being on vacation and on the beach and swimming and not working.

02:39.896 --> 02:42.019
But I am glad to be with you guys this morning.

02:42.680 --> 02:44.322
And maybe we're working some things out.

02:44.443 --> 02:45.564
Microphone, we good?

02:45.764 --> 02:46.085
Michael?

02:46.405 --> 02:47.286
OK, perfect.

02:47.306 --> 02:56.078
So today is not only the 12th Sunday in this little season that we've been calling summertime, but it is also our final Sunday in this season.

02:56.118 --> 02:58.962
Next Sunday, we're going to be kicking off a new season.

02:59.490 --> 03:03.797
one which Pete is going to tell you more about, but it is the season of creation.

03:04.358 --> 03:10.668
This has been a more recent addition to the church calendar by many of our more liturgical brothers and sisters around the world.

03:10.708 --> 03:20.864
And we thought we would jump on board as well as we continue to deepen our commitment and awareness of the importance of caring for the rest of creation as a part of our spiritual formation.

03:20.884 --> 03:26.994
So we'll have four weeks of that starting next Sunday, which will absolutely include our time up at Big Lake.

03:27.714 --> 03:28.735
You've been with us this summer.

03:28.755 --> 03:32.900
You know that we have spent this entire season in the book of Genesis.

03:32.940 --> 03:34.322
We started at the beginning.

03:34.342 --> 03:37.226
We talked about the first creation account in Genesis 1.

03:37.646 --> 03:46.878
I looked at the second creation account, the fall, Cain and Abel, the flood, the Tower of Babel, the call of Abraham, Hagar and Ishmael, Abraham, Isaac, Jacob, Esau.

03:47.619 --> 03:49.421
And last week we talked about Rachel and Leon.

03:50.242 --> 03:56.850
And so that got us through the first 30 chapters of Genesis, which means I have today to wrap up the remaining 20 chapters.

03:57.282 --> 03:59.384
So I hope you went to the bathroom before you got here.

03:59.404 --> 04:00.706
We're going to be a little while.

04:02.168 --> 04:07.494
If you remember from way back in the beginning, we said that Genesis is split into two main chunks, chapters 1 through 11.

04:07.914 --> 04:09.596
That's known as the primeval history.

04:09.917 --> 04:14.462
And then chapters 12 through 50 is known as the story of the patriarchs.

04:14.482 --> 04:24.914
In the second section of Genesis, the recurring theme is this, that there are these big famous characters that we know as the patriarchs, and they keep messing up.

04:25.186 --> 04:32.333
They keep failing, they keep falling short, but in the midst of their failure, God remains faithful.

04:33.054 --> 04:37.359
No matter how much they screw up, God is faithful to them and to his people.

04:38.159 --> 04:43.285
No Pete showed a family tree a few weeks ago, so we're gonna add on to it for how we got to our text today.

04:43.785 --> 04:52.114
We started there at the top with Abraham and where we remember that God promised that all of the families of the earth would be blessed through him.

04:52.610 --> 04:53.752
We talked about Hagar.

04:53.792 --> 04:57.238
We offered you maybe a different perspective on Hagar than you've heard before.

04:57.258 --> 05:00.503
We discussed Ishmael and Isaac as Abraham's sons.

05:01.424 --> 05:08.095
And then we get to Jacob and you see there between four different wives, Jacob had 12 sons.

05:08.837 --> 05:14.546
The text also tells us that Jacob has daughters, plural,

05:14.722 --> 05:19.166
But they don't ever really get mentioned other than Dina is one of them.

05:19.687 --> 05:20.768
So I guess Barbie was right.

05:20.808 --> 05:21.889
The patriarchy is real.

05:23.351 --> 05:25.813
It was totally overlooked in the story of the 12 tribes.

05:25.833 --> 05:34.742
So as we get to Joseph, which is highlighted there on the bottom, he really is the main character of this final section of Genesis.

05:35.162 --> 05:42.770
And in this big picture narrative of Genesis, Joseph's story actually serves as a microcosm for the entire story.

05:43.234 --> 05:48.599
One commentator describes the Joseph story as Genesis breaking into full bloom.

05:49.440 --> 05:54.985
Because it is in this narrative that we see the themes of this entire book come to life.

05:55.826 --> 05:59.509
It's a narrative that happened here in Genesis and elsewhere in Scripture.

05:59.549 --> 06:05.495
They aren't just present to tell you this happened, then this happened, then this happened.

06:05.535 --> 06:08.118
They are not just a recording of events.

06:08.218 --> 06:09.459
They make a different claim.

06:09.519 --> 06:12.882
They say, look at the world like this.

06:13.794 --> 06:16.879
They don't just chronicle events, they configure them.

06:17.360 --> 06:21.627
They want you to see the world differently because of how these narratives are told.

06:21.647 --> 06:24.491
The details that are included are included for a reason.

06:24.511 --> 06:33.847
If you remember from week one, we said that these stories in Genesis may have been written down by a people in exile trying to reclaim their heritage.

06:34.348 --> 06:38.354
So we'll use that prism as we view these texts today as well.

06:38.498 --> 06:44.165
Since we'll be covering the entire story of Joseph, a few background notes to get us up to speed.

06:44.805 --> 06:47.809
At the time of our story, Joseph is 17.

06:47.869 --> 06:53.035
We also learned that Jacob loved Joseph more than any of his other sons.

06:53.956 --> 06:54.517
So why is that?

06:54.577 --> 06:57.220
Maybe you have a favorite child too.

06:57.280 --> 07:00.304
Sometimes it can be explained, sometimes it can't, right?

07:00.464 --> 07:03.668
I'm not sure why I'm my parents favorite, but I just am.

07:04.729 --> 07:05.810
For Jacob,

07:06.178 --> 07:07.279
It can be explained.

07:07.299 --> 07:16.350
So if we pull up that family tree one more time, I know it's kind of hard to read all of the names in the back, but, again, Jacob had sons with four wives, Rachel, Leah, Zilpa, and Bilha.

07:17.271 --> 07:19.714
If you remember, Linda's great sermon last week.

07:19.794 --> 07:21.957
Jacob originally wanted to marry Rachel.

07:21.997 --> 07:27.083
That was who he really loved, but their father tricked him into marrying Leah first.

07:27.704 --> 07:36.114
And in their fight to bear sons for Jacob, both sisters had Jacob conceived children with their maids, Zilpa and Bilha.

07:36.578 --> 07:45.073
In fact, Rachel bore Jacob no children until after Leah, Billha, and Zilpa had between them given birth to 10 sons.

07:45.674 --> 07:47.256
And we don't know how many other daughters.

07:48.278 --> 07:58.476
So when Rachel, the woman that he truly loved all along, the one he wanted as his wife in the first place, finally conceived, she gave birth to Joseph.

07:59.057 --> 08:02.162
And then she died giving birth to Benjamin, to Benjamin.

08:02.722 --> 08:11.114
So the beloved and favored wife of Jacob, the one he worked 14 years for, died after giving him two sons, the oldest of which was Joseph.

08:11.214 --> 08:14.879
That is why he is Jacob's favorite.

08:14.899 --> 08:16.721
He is the firstborn of his true love.

08:16.741 --> 08:22.349
And Jacob marks his favoritism for Joseph by giving him an ornate robe.

08:22.930 --> 08:26.555
We're not entirely sure what it looked like, but here's a picture of what it could have looked like.

08:28.538 --> 08:28.818
Yeah.

08:29.442 --> 08:38.532
So if you are a Broadway fan, you know that this is the amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat as depicted in Seinfeld, and this may be a bit of an exaggeration.

08:39.133 --> 08:48.864
But whatever it looked like, it was a gift that only Joseph got, and we know that it wasn't intended for manual labor.

08:49.684 --> 08:51.707
This set him apart, a special different.

08:51.727 --> 08:53.769
And so it's no surprise to learn this.

08:53.849 --> 08:58.354
When his brother saw that their father loved him more than any of them,

08:58.786 --> 09:02.130
They hated him and could not speak a kind work to him.

09:02.971 --> 09:05.734
This is a motif that we've seen throughout Genesis.

09:05.814 --> 09:15.485
If you remember back even to our Cain and Abel discussion, we said that older siblings would not look so good throughout Genesis, and it's come true time and time again.

09:15.505 --> 09:24.535
Younger siblings have been shown favor, but unfortunately that favor has led to even greater hardship and sometimes even death.

09:24.675 --> 09:27.058
Joseph will go through this same experience.

09:27.554 --> 09:31.120
That's not to say that Joseph is entirely innocent either.

09:31.160 --> 09:34.665
The first thing that we actually learn about Joseph is that he's a tattle tale.

09:35.747 --> 09:39.653
He brings a bad report about his brothers and their shepherding skills to Jacob.

09:40.334 --> 09:48.187
And while it can be typical sibling behavior to think a parent prefers one child over another, you know, Jacob has no chill about it, right?

09:48.207 --> 09:52.514
You know, you 11 go work in the fields and you, Joseph, take this code.

09:52.534 --> 09:55.218
You're too pretty to, you know, go work out in the fields.

09:56.066 --> 09:59.730
It's not a great idea to build those bonds of brotherly love.

10:00.291 --> 10:03.154
And if you remember the story, Joseph, he has two dreams.

10:03.714 --> 10:12.784
And the main point in each of the dreams that he has is that all of his brothers would bow down before him eventually.

10:13.765 --> 10:20.173
And I don't know if Joseph is clueless or if this is his kind of serious little brother energy.

10:20.953 --> 10:25.138
But he tells his brothers who he already knows hate him

10:25.314 --> 10:26.636
about this dream.

10:27.517 --> 10:29.800
It seems like a really bad read of the room.

10:29.880 --> 10:36.750
I mean, had journaling not been invented yet, you don't tell your brothers who don't like you that they're all going to bow down before you.

10:37.551 --> 10:45.202
And so he seems to be taking full advantage of the favored status, but Jacob even ends up rebuking him for these dreams.

10:45.666 --> 10:55.719
He may be living in the shadow of his brothers for now, but it's clear that Joseph has dreams of being the top dog just like his dad did when he was a younger brother as well.

10:56.621 --> 11:02.528
And as our text for today begins, Jacob has sent Joseph to check in on his brothers.

11:02.548 --> 11:04.110
That's not going to be the first time that I do that.

11:04.611 --> 11:06.834
And they are shepherding out in the fields.

11:07.042 --> 11:10.708
They are a long way from home, but eventually Joseph finds them.

11:10.748 --> 11:19.763
And as he approaches them, maybe they think he is going to tattle on them again, or maybe they just had enough of the whole situation, they decide they're going to kill him.

11:19.783 --> 11:22.948
So verse 19 says, here comes that dreamer.

11:23.529 --> 11:31.602
They said to each other, come now, let's kill him and throw him into one of these cisterns and say that a ferocious animal devoured him.

11:31.622 --> 11:33.906
Then we'll see what comes of his dreams.

11:34.882 --> 11:37.426
Now there are two perspectives on these dreams for Joseph.

11:37.826 --> 11:42.013
His dreams indicate a future and a prospect to be celebrated.

11:42.333 --> 11:47.121
It's a promise to be kept that he is going to be in charge, that he is going to be the boss.

11:48.262 --> 11:54.933
For the brothers, Joseph's dreams articulate a future threat that must be resisted at all costs.

11:54.953 --> 12:03.826
Their logic goes like this, if we kill the dreamer, then the dreams can't come true, which I think is also the plot to the movie Minority Report, but I'm not sure.

12:05.090 --> 12:06.151
That's right, Tom Cruise.

12:06.392 --> 12:10.396
But as it turns out, not everyone was okay with this plan.

12:10.456 --> 12:13.140
Ruben, the oldest child, he talks some sense in him.

12:13.160 --> 12:18.086
He tries to rescue Joseph, and it's still not a great plan or situation.

12:18.706 --> 12:20.148
We'll just throw him into a cistern.

12:20.228 --> 12:25.154
But with this idea, the brothers would be satiated, at least a little.

12:25.174 --> 12:31.602
But Joseph would have some time to learn his lesson, and then they could all move forward as a family.

12:32.674 --> 12:36.700
good big brother, oldest brother stuff, calm right here.

12:36.740 --> 12:47.598
And when Joseph shows up, they take his fancy jacket, they throw him in the cistern, and after all that hard work of tormenting their brother, they've worked up an appetite so they sit down to have a meal.

12:48.639 --> 12:55.410
Apparently Reuben has left during this meal because Judah hatches a new plan, and it sure sounds like

12:55.490 --> 12:57.813
They never wanted to follow Ruben's plan.

12:57.974 --> 13:04.303
Anyway, in verse 26, Judah said to his brothers, what will we gain if we kill our brother and cover up his blood?

13:05.204 --> 13:08.849
Come, let's sell him to the Ishmaelites and not lay our hands on him.

13:08.929 --> 13:11.853
After all, he is our brother, our own flesh and blood.

13:12.294 --> 13:13.075
His brothers agreed.

13:13.836 --> 13:17.702
So we see that the brothers don't just eliminate Joseph as a problem.

13:17.742 --> 13:19.204
They make a profit off him.

13:20.145 --> 13:23.410
They sell him into slavery for 20 shekels of silver,

13:23.970 --> 13:30.178
Verse 29, Reuben returns to get Joseph out of the hole, but quickly finds out what the brothers have done.

13:30.858 --> 13:33.922
He tears his clothes, he's overcome with grief.

13:35.144 --> 13:36.525
And what do the other brothers do?

13:36.565 --> 13:38.528
Well, the text gives us nothing.

13:38.548 --> 13:43.594
There is no response from the other brothers other than to cover their crime.

13:44.836 --> 13:46.718
They never express remorse here.

13:46.758 --> 13:53.426
They take Joseph's coat, they cover in blood, and they present it to Jacob as proof of Joseph's death.

13:54.274 --> 14:00.282
While they may not have Joseph's literal blood on their hands, they know that they have signed his death warrant.

14:00.302 --> 14:04.669
They want someone else to take care of that problem, and they are guilty of the crime.

14:05.730 --> 14:14.162
What will come to light eventually as the story progresses is that this guilt never leaves the brothers throughout this whole story.

14:14.882 --> 14:23.097
In Shakespeare's Macbeth, after Macbeth kills Duncan, he goes to Lady Macbeth with his hands, covered in blood, and he's horrified with what he's done.

14:23.137 --> 14:29.888
And in a famous line, he says, will all great Neptune's ocean wash this blood clean from my hand?

14:30.890 --> 14:31.792
And the answer is no.

14:32.633 --> 14:37.061
And just like Macbeth, the brothers will realize that this guilt stays with them.

14:37.101 --> 14:39.826
They can't escape what they have done.

14:40.738 --> 14:42.160
So what happens in the rest of the story?

14:42.200 --> 14:45.906
You know the gist of it, but some of the high points rather quickly.

14:46.948 --> 14:49.051
Potiphar is the captain of Pharaoh's guard.

14:49.491 --> 14:55.821
He buys Joseph as a slave, and because the Lord is with him, he quickly rises to the head of Potiphar's house.

14:56.442 --> 15:00.148
Unfortunately, Potiphar's wife takes interest in Joseph.

15:00.669 --> 15:06.738
She tries to seduce him, and when he refuses, he is framed for trying to commit adultery with her enthrone in prison.

15:07.458 --> 15:11.683
Yet in prison, the Lord is with him, and the prison warden put him in charge of all the other prisoners.

15:12.463 --> 15:20.312
If you remember, there's a cup bearer, there's a baker, and eventually Pharaoh has a dream that needs interpreting, and Joseph is selected for this task.

15:20.332 --> 15:28.841
Because the Lord was with him, he is able to interpret these dreams, which help Egypt prepare for a famine, and saves the lives of countless people.

15:29.502 --> 15:37.010
So Joseph is raised up again, he's put in charge of all of Egypt, and during this famine, Joseph's brothers, minus Benjamin,

15:37.250 --> 15:39.835
One who had the same momma said, make their way down to Egypt.

15:40.275 --> 15:41.698
And Joseph, he tests them a bit.

15:42.539 --> 15:44.062
They're put in prison for a couple days.

15:44.543 --> 15:52.076
They're questioned, and eventually they're told they must bring Benjamin back to Egypt to prove that they are telling the truth about their story.

15:52.877 --> 16:02.514
Joseph lays out one final test, putting a silver cup in Benjamin's bag, framing him as a thief, and claiming him as a slave because of his treachery.

16:03.490 --> 16:05.833
But here is where we see a change in the brothers.

16:05.913 --> 16:16.106
Judas says this, now then please let your servant remain here as my Lord's slave in place of the boy, in place of Benjamin, and let the boy return with his brothers.

16:17.128 --> 16:18.710
We'll come back and talk about why that's important.

16:18.730 --> 16:23.496
But Joseph finally makes himself known to his brothers and they weep and they embrace one another.

16:23.516 --> 16:26.159
They return home to fetch Jacob and the rest of the family.

16:26.640 --> 16:31.186
And they end up living in Egypt, writing out the famine and living happily ever after.

16:32.418 --> 16:32.758
Kind of.

16:34.861 --> 16:35.262
Not at all.

16:35.702 --> 16:39.988
In the midst of the rest of this narrative, there are two main themes that come to the surface.

16:40.388 --> 16:43.092
And the first one is actually all about ups and downs.

16:43.152 --> 16:45.775
We heard this in the brief summary there, but it bears repeating.

16:46.196 --> 16:51.002
Joseph has several literal and metaphorical ascents and descents.

16:51.522 --> 16:52.904
He's put down into the pit.

16:52.924 --> 16:54.486
He's taken down to Egypt.

16:54.506 --> 17:00.754
He ascends to a position of authority and pot of first house, but descends to prison after false accusations.

17:01.378 --> 17:03.540
rises again to a position of authority.

17:03.560 --> 17:07.525
But to send the surprising one more time, the cut bear finally remembers him.

17:07.545 --> 17:11.770
He's raised from the pit to the highest position possible for him in Egypt.

17:11.830 --> 17:16.955
Literally and metaphorically, he has experienced every up and down imaginable.

17:18.056 --> 17:19.158
But the second theme is this.

17:19.278 --> 17:26.586
In the midst of the ups and downs, there is one phrase that is repeated over and over, and that is the Lord was with Joseph.

17:27.747 --> 17:30.290
The Lord was with him in the pit.

17:30.626 --> 17:39.059
in the prison, in the positions of authority God was present with him, no matter how high he ascended or how low he descended.

17:41.362 --> 17:46.850
But one thing we don't think about is how God was also with Joseph's brothers as well.

17:47.611 --> 17:50.115
God pursued them as they tried to hide their guilt.

17:50.556 --> 17:57.586
And as the brothers accept the tests from Joseph, and we hear Judah instead offer up himself in the place of Benjamin,

17:58.210 --> 18:01.778
they recognize that God has been caring for them all along too.

18:02.740 --> 18:07.410
God has been working in their lives and in their hearts and it's brought about a change in them.

18:07.450 --> 18:18.194
They've gone from being willing to kill and to sell their brother into slavery to being willing to give up their own lives in freedom to save another one of their brothers.

18:19.458 --> 18:23.683
Seems that Judah and the other brothers, they've changed over the course of their story.

18:23.723 --> 18:25.025
Gone is the intense hatred.

18:25.085 --> 18:27.728
They once held for the favored son of their father.

18:27.748 --> 18:32.574
There's no hint that they envy or hate Benjamin now who holds that special place.

18:33.555 --> 18:40.424
They bear the guilt of what they did to Joseph, interpreting the trouble that they're experiencing as punishment for what they did long ago.

18:40.444 --> 18:48.754
Now they have matured over the course of these years apart and they are determined to save Benjamin.

18:50.306 --> 18:55.233
But all of this is only able to happen because of one thing.

18:56.575 --> 18:57.356
And that's forgiveness.

18:59.299 --> 19:02.744
Joseph offers them forgiveness in our Antioch language.

19:02.764 --> 19:04.066
We talk about reconciliation.

19:04.927 --> 19:14.962
When Joseph's brothers showed up in Egypt, it would have been very easy to treat him according to the law of mutual justice.

19:15.618 --> 19:17.521
You all tried to kill me.

19:17.581 --> 19:19.904
You'd sold me as a slave.

19:20.064 --> 19:24.671
I am going to do the exact same thing to you, what you did to me.

19:24.731 --> 19:25.432
It's only fair.

19:26.974 --> 19:32.341
He had the might of Egypt at his back to do whatever he ordered them to do.

19:33.683 --> 19:44.178
But instead of choosing to treat them with this idea of mutual justice, Joseph chooses to treat them in line with the example of God's grace.

19:45.730 --> 19:46.751
Why is he able to do that?

19:47.973 --> 19:51.598
After all of what he has experienced, why is he able to do that?

19:53.300 --> 20:04.756
I hunch his, it's because he is confident that God has been with him, even in his circumstances, even in his life, when it felt just like the opposite of God being present.

20:05.758 --> 20:14.610
In chapter 45, when Joseph reveals himself to his brothers for the first time, he says this, I am your brother, Joseph.

20:15.234 --> 20:23.305
the one you sold in slavery in Egypt, and now do not be distressed and do not be angry with yourselves for selling me here.

20:24.607 --> 20:26.990
Because it was to save lives that God sent me ahead of you.

20:27.871 --> 20:41.330
For two years now, there has been famine in the land, and for the next five years, there will be no plowing and reaping, but God sent me ahead of you to preserve for you a remnant on earth and to save your lives by a great deliverance.

20:42.498 --> 20:47.506
That is some seriously aspirational maturity from Joseph right there.

20:48.327 --> 20:53.375
In the next verse, he would go on to say, so then it was not you who sent me here, but God.

20:54.957 --> 20:59.644
Which stirs up all sorts of other theological questions, right?

20:59.724 --> 21:01.307
Why did God do this?

21:01.367 --> 21:05.213
If I was Joseph, I would be saying, God, why would you do this to me?

21:05.313 --> 21:06.315
All that I went through.

21:07.036 --> 21:11.122
And we have to ask the question, is this how God works in the world?

21:11.906 --> 21:24.203
And Joseph offers more clarity in the last chapter of Genesis when he has one final statement to comfort his brothers who are still afraid for his retribution once their father Jacob has passed.

21:24.383 --> 21:40.466
And he says this, Joseph makes it clear that he doesn't attribute the brother's sinful actions to God.

21:41.218 --> 21:42.720
God did not make them sin.

21:42.780 --> 21:48.206
God did not instruct them to do what they did to Joseph, to put them in the pit, to sell them into slavery.

21:48.246 --> 21:50.289
God did not tell them to do that.

21:51.430 --> 21:52.411
Joseph makes that clear.

21:52.471 --> 22:00.100
But what Joseph does affirm is that God was able to use those sinful actions for God's own good purposes.

22:01.762 --> 22:05.106
The brothers devised evil, but God turned it to good.

22:05.698 --> 22:15.810
that all along God's intention was to preserve life, preserve the life of the family, of Jacob, the lives of many people, including all of the Egyptians, everyone who would experience this famine.

22:16.650 --> 22:22.797
Joseph's presence in Egypt is the means by which God ensures that life will go on.

22:24.559 --> 22:32.849
Reverend Dr. Carolyn Helsel, she is a pastor and a preaching professor, and she says this about what Joseph is able to do here at the end of the story.

22:32.909 --> 22:33.810
She says,

22:33.954 --> 22:44.209
This kind of integrative meaning making happens when we can accept the pain of the wounds of suffering and also see what positive contributions we have made in the world.

22:45.671 --> 22:48.936
Joseph did not have to deny the pain of what his brothers did to him to heal.

22:49.637 --> 23:03.538
By God's grace, he was able to see how the misfortune and injustice he experienced led him to a position of power and privilege where he could bring healing and justice to many people.

23:04.258 --> 23:18.684
She is articulating here is that what we see in Joseph, it's not a shallow or a hokey, you know, everything happens for a reason cliche, but instead a raw experience that doesn't overlook the pain that he's gone through.

23:20.487 --> 23:21.970
There aren't cheap platitudes.

23:22.090 --> 23:28.722
He is able to acknowledge his hurt, his grief, his pain, where his life has sucked.

23:29.954 --> 23:37.001
but he is able to look backward after the fact and see all of it through a different prism because of the presence of God.

23:38.522 --> 23:48.052
This place of knowing that God has been with him through every up and down is the place where he is able to actually draw the ability to forgive his brothers.

23:50.134 --> 23:56.800
And this power that lies in forgiveness, it's a theme that comes up in Lin-Manuel Miranda's musical Hamilton.

23:56.820 --> 23:57.701
Any fans out there?

23:58.542 --> 23:58.642
Yeah.

23:59.554 --> 24:04.902
So if you haven't seen it in person, you can always watch it on Disney Plus, not quite the same, but still good.

24:05.503 --> 24:07.226
And anyway, you know the story.

24:07.246 --> 24:10.591
It's about the life of Alexander Hamilton, one of our founding fathers.

24:10.631 --> 24:14.416
And I would give a spoiler warning, but this stuff happened like 250 years ago.

24:14.517 --> 24:16.940
So I think the grace period is over.

24:17.000 --> 24:24.211
But late in the story, Hamilton has seriously messed up.

24:24.231 --> 24:28.658
He committed adultery against his wife, Eliza, and they have just

24:28.994 --> 24:34.865
lost their son to death in a duel that was essentially instigated to protect Hamilton's reputation.

24:36.107 --> 24:37.530
He bears the blame for this.

24:38.451 --> 24:44.021
And in one of the most beautiful and tear-inducing songs of the show, it's called It's Quiet Uptown.

24:45.684 --> 24:49.331
It details Hamilton's efforts to make things right with the Liza.

24:50.654 --> 24:53.138
He knows that he doesn't deserve forgiveness.

24:54.242 --> 25:05.712
In the song, it crescendos, talking about how there are moments that words just don't reach, that there is a grace too powerful to name until it finally says forgiveness.

25:06.474 --> 25:08.018
Can you imagine?

25:08.962 --> 25:12.106
Can you imagine the power of forgiveness?

25:12.187 --> 25:24.624
In contrast to so many of the other songs, the smooth talking Hamilton, he doesn't seem to have the words to say because he can't fathom this grace that is too powerful to name, that is found in forgiveness.

25:26.527 --> 25:33.116
Eliza forgives him and they begin their journey of deep reconciliation together and he probably doesn't deserve forgiveness.

25:34.678 --> 25:37.522
But forgiveness is rarely ever about what we deserve.

25:38.818 --> 25:48.413
If you remember when we started, we talked about how the narratives in scripture don't just give an account of things that happen, they're formulated so that we see the world differently.

25:49.395 --> 25:59.631
And in this story, which serves as a microcosm for the entire narrative of Genesis, it recognizes both the hiddenness of God and it also emphasizes the imminence of God.

26:00.633 --> 26:06.322
What I mean is that this story takes place between the hint of the dream that began

26:06.498 --> 26:16.015
Joseph's dream of what was to come takes place between that and the doxology of his disclosure there in Genesis 50, that God was working all along.

26:17.016 --> 26:31.602
And as this narrative was told to its original audience who were living between the oldest promises of Israel and what God would do, what God had promised for them, and they were living between this other pole, the groans of the slaves anticipating their freedom.

26:32.098 --> 26:40.089
that as they lived in the middle, this story was meant to model these truths, that God is working all along even when you can't see it.

26:40.790 --> 26:45.156
And because of that, the people of God are be a people that practice forgiveness.

26:46.478 --> 26:57.874
And even when it doesn't make sense, they were to continue the forgiving way of life and to seek reconciliation wherever necessary because it is an essential part of Shalom.

26:58.690 --> 27:04.740
If this is where Genesis breaks into full bloom, it's because of this paradigm of grace and forgiveness.

27:06.342 --> 27:12.472
And forgiveness is so powerful, it's even recommended as a healthy lifestyle choice by the Mayo Clinic.

27:13.494 --> 27:14.836
They say, I look this up.

27:15.296 --> 27:23.890
They say, when you forgive someone, it can lead to improved mental health, less anxiety, fewer symptoms of depression, lower blood pressure, and improved heart health.

27:24.898 --> 27:26.300
It also has communal outcomes.

27:26.320 --> 27:32.529
It can change how entire groups of people relate to each other and allow people to move past revenge and to cooperation.

27:33.851 --> 27:43.424
In our story, we can ask the question, without Joseph's forgiveness of his brothers, do we get everything that comes after?

27:44.866 --> 27:50.314
If Joseph's favorite Bible verse was an eye for an eye, what happens in our story, right?

27:50.354 --> 27:53.458
There might not be 12 tribes.

27:54.466 --> 27:57.049
There might not be Judah, the tribe of Judah.

27:57.069 --> 27:58.892
There is no line of David.

27:58.972 --> 28:01.996
Where does the Messiah come from?

28:02.997 --> 28:06.502
The fulcrum of this story is whether Joseph will forgive or not.

28:06.582 --> 28:09.766
And this is what the original audience needed to hear.

28:09.826 --> 28:17.216
This is how they were to hear this narrative so that they would see the world differently and live differently because of it.

28:18.798 --> 28:21.842
Ultimately for you and I, we would get to experience something

28:22.082 --> 28:28.149
would come a little bit after Joseph's time, and that is the forgiveness and reconciliation that's found in Jesus.

28:29.250 --> 28:39.182
Forgiveness was one of Jesus' most often talked about topics, parables, practical advice, talking about how necessary it is to forgive how often we are to do it.

28:39.242 --> 28:45.530
He said 70 times, seven times, basically that we should be doing it all the time.

28:45.550 --> 28:49.234
It should be a part of our lives every single day,

28:49.794 --> 28:52.959
Theologian John Whitvlett puts it better than I ever could.

28:53.039 --> 28:55.883
He said, we don't forgive because it benefits us.

28:56.704 --> 29:14.610
Those benefits may be a welcome byproduct, but our motivation to forgive is rooted in God's call to forgive, our gratitude for God's forgiveness of us, and our desire to imitate Christ, the one who perfectly modeled forgiveness, and even now perfects our efforts to practice forgiveness.

29:16.002 --> 29:18.826
So yes, all those personal health benefits are great.

29:18.906 --> 29:20.068
I want lower blood pressure.

29:20.969 --> 29:27.418
So is changing our community for the better, but ultimately we are to forgive because Christ first forgave us.

29:28.359 --> 29:31.423
It's not just something that we do as followers of Jesus.

29:31.624 --> 29:33.847
It is who we are.

29:33.887 --> 29:41.177
It's an essential part of our everyday work of taking up our crosses just as it was for those ancient Israelites.

29:42.078 --> 29:44.722
Forgiveness and our commitment to forgive

29:44.802 --> 29:47.707
should make us different from the world.

29:48.569 --> 29:50.252
Should make us stand out.

29:50.292 --> 29:54.660
It should be our defining characteristics of how we have relationships.

29:54.680 --> 29:56.723
It should be how we enter into the world.

29:58.106 --> 29:59.308
Unfortunately, we're not great at it.

30:00.089 --> 30:00.570
I'm not great.

30:00.590 --> 30:04.958
That's not top of the list of what we are known for as Christians here in America.

30:06.460 --> 30:09.586
And yet, I remain hopeful for a better way.

30:10.498 --> 30:26.740
Because I believe that a revolution that starts with the people committed to living the Jesus way, the way of forgiveness, the way of humility, the way of reconciliation, the way of laying down your life, even for those whom you vehemently disagree with is coming.

30:27.761 --> 30:35.532
And it starts with you and me, and it starts with us offering forgiveness in our own lives to our spouses, to our friends, to our kids.

30:36.032 --> 30:40.338
Sometimes those closest to us are the hardest ones for us to forgive.

30:41.890 --> 30:43.772
Maybe it's to our coworkers.

30:43.852 --> 30:48.097
Maybe it's to the guy who drives too slow or the jerk who cuts you off, right?

30:48.117 --> 30:52.722
To your former boss that you've been holding it against them for a long time.

30:53.623 --> 30:59.490
To your ex, to that friend who you don't see anymore because it hasn't been the same since they did that one thing.

31:00.531 --> 31:05.336
To the person who voted differently than you and it's all their fault that your candidate lost.

31:06.277 --> 31:08.039
Or to the politician that you didn't vote for.

31:09.101 --> 31:10.322
To the person you just

31:10.434 --> 31:12.637
saw a trash on the ground in the litter.

31:13.438 --> 31:15.021
That one works in my heart, right?

31:15.101 --> 31:17.965
It's up to us to practice forgiveness.

31:18.666 --> 31:25.015
No matter who it is, no matter how hard it is, or no matter how undeserving it feels, we must choose forgiveness.

31:25.056 --> 31:32.847
Because the way of Jesus is not about being right all the time or fixing other people, and it's not about deserving forgiveness either.

31:32.867 --> 31:40.338
It's about emulating Jesus' complete commitment to forgiveness, even when it means losing the upper hand.

31:41.442 --> 31:42.103
And that's hard.

31:42.884 --> 31:43.786
And I am bad at it.

31:44.787 --> 31:49.033
But I am committed to doing it with each one of you because we have to ask ourselves these questions.

31:49.755 --> 31:54.442
What if my choosing to forgive is a part of the advancing of the kingdom of God?

31:55.884 --> 31:57.626
Because that's what happened here in our story.

31:58.848 --> 32:03.736
That Joseph's willingness to forgive, advance the kingdom of God in huge ways.

32:04.677 --> 32:05.178
No better yet.

32:06.099 --> 32:07.922
Who can I forgive today?

32:08.194 --> 32:11.780
as we work towards the reconciliation of all things.

32:12.802 --> 32:17.470
We might not make it to all things if I can't reconcile my own relationships with each other's.

32:18.452 --> 32:20.456
So who in your life do you need to forgive?

32:20.516 --> 32:21.918
It could be a long time.

32:21.938 --> 32:23.281
It could be just yesterday.

32:23.301 --> 32:24.402
It could be a group of people.

32:24.463 --> 32:25.665
It could be a way of thinking.

32:25.685 --> 32:28.690
How can forgiveness enter your life today?

32:28.834 --> 32:40.126
Because what we see in the story of Joseph is that forgiveness and reconciliation are essential parts of building the kingdom of God that Christ inaugurated and will be eventually completed in the reconciliation of all things.

32:40.547 --> 32:43.009
That we offer a foretaste when we forgive.

32:43.990 --> 32:50.597
And just like in this story, we may not see God's hand at work all the time, he may feel distant or like he's not even there at all.

32:51.338 --> 32:58.546
But when we model forgiveness, we are saying that we trust that God is working in the midst of this situation and will take

32:58.690 --> 33:11.850
evil intentions and bad things and use them for good, that God is working to preserve life and working towards Shalom, that maybe it's unforgiveness that our faith breaks out into full bloom as well.

33:12.812 --> 33:18.280
So Antioch family, may our defining characteristic be that we are a people of forgiveness.

33:18.921 --> 33:19.282
Amen.

